<BaseLayout
  title="Why Old Songs Still Make Money | How Much Music"
  description="Why evergreen songs stay commercially active through playlists, nostalgia, licensing, and repeat listening decades after release."
  type="article"
>
  <section>
    <p class="eyebrow">Explainer</p>
    <h1>Why old songs still make money</h1>
    <p>
      Evergreen songs survive because they stay useful. They fit playlists, trigger nostalgia,
      support sync use, and remain legible to new listeners long after their release cycle is over.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Main drivers</h2>
    <ul class="meta-list">
      <li>Editorial and algorithmic playlists keep classic tracks in circulation.</li>
      <li>Nostalgia creates repeat listening across multiple generations.</li>
      <li>Film, TV, trailers, and internet culture repeatedly reintroduce older songs.</li>
      <li>Holiday, wedding, workout, and mood-based listening can create repeatable yearly demand.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>What makes a song evergreen</h2>
    <p>
      Evergreen value usually comes from usefulness. A song that fits many listening situations can
      keep earning after radio promotion ends because each new context creates another reason to
      replay it.
    </p>
    <p>
      Some evergreen tracks are seasonal, some are emotionally durable, and some are licensing
      machines. The strongest ones combine several of those patterns, which is why their annual
      earnings can remain meaningful long after the original chart peak.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Evergreen signals used on song pages</h2>
    <ul class="meta-list">
      <li>Repeatable annual demand, such as holiday, wedding, workout, nostalgia, or mood-based listening.</li>
      <li>Evidence that the song works outside its release year, such as recurring platform visibility or media reuse.</li>
      <li>Ownership notes that clarify whether long-tail value likely reaches the artist, estate, label, publisher, or catalog buyer.</li>
      <li>Related-song context that shows whether the song is exceptional within its own artist catalog.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Why it matters for artists</h2>
    <p>
      Music is one of the few creative assets that can keep generating income for decades. That is
      why catalog ownership, licensing rights, and long-tail relevance matter so much.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>How evergreen value is modeled</h2>
    <ul class="meta-list">
      <li>Older songs with persistent replay get more credit than songs with one short viral spike.</li>
      <li>Sync-friendly songs can justify stronger catalog assumptions than streaming alone suggests.</li>
      <li>Holiday and event songs are treated as seasonal assets because their demand is concentrated but repeatable.</li>
      <li>Ownership notes still matter because evergreen gross revenue is not the same as artist-side income.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
